{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ring Final Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit that starts at the consumer unit, loops through all outlets, and returns to the same starting point.",
      "anchor": "A continuous loop that shares the electrical load between two paths.",
      "misconception": "Thinking a ring is just a long radial; it must return to the source to function as a ring."
    },
    {
      "term": "Radial Circuit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A circuit that runs from the consumer unit to the points of use and ends at the final outlet.",
      "anchor": "A single path from the source to the last point, like a branch on a tree.",
      "misconception": "Believing radials are only for lighting; they are also used for high-power appliances like cookers."
    },
    {
      "term": "SWA (Steel Wire Armoured)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A cable with a layer of steel wires around the insulation to provide high mechanical protection.",
      "anchor": "The heavy-duty cable used for underground runs or industrial floors.",
      "misconception": "Thinking the steel wire is a power conductor; it is for physical protection and earthing."
    },
    {
      "term": "MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad)",
      "simpleDefinition": "A fire-resistant cable made of copper conductors inside a copper sheath, packed with mineral powder.",
      "anchor": "The ultimate fire-proof cable for emergency systems and high-heat areas.",
      "misconception": "Thinking it is standard cable; it requires specialized seals to prevent moisture from ruining the mineral insulation."
    },
    {
      "term": "Conduit",
      "simpleDefinition": "A protective tube, usually plastic or metal, used to house and protect individual cables.",
      "anchor": "A rigid pipe used to shield cables from physical impact.",
      "misconception": "Thinking conduit is just for aesthetics; its primary job is mechanical protection and allowing for easy rewiring."
    },
    {
      "term": "Trunking",
      "simpleDefinition": "A rectangular enclosure with a removable lid used to carry multiple cables along walls or ceilings.",
      "anchor": "A box-section channel that makes managing large groups of cables easy.",
      "misconception": "Confusing trunking with conduit; trunking has a removable lid, while conduit is a solid tube."
    },
    {
      "term": "Hazardous Environment",
      "simpleDefinition": "An area where flammable gases, vapours, or dusts create a risk of fire or explosion.",
      "anchor": "A high-risk zone requiring specialized, spark-proof wiring systems.",
      "misconception": "Thinking 'hazardous' just means 'dangerous'; in wiring, it specifically refers to explosive atmospheres."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "A continuous loop that shares the electrical load",
    "A single path from the source to the last point",
    "Mechanical protection for harsh environments",
    "Fire-resistant wiring for emergency circuits",
    "Enclosures for protecting and routing cables"
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Ring circuits must return to the consumer unit to be valid.",
    "Radial circuits are not limited to lighting; they serve power loads too.",
    "SWA steel is for protection, not for carrying live current.",
    "Trunking is defined by its removable lid, unlike conduit.",
    "Hazardous environments require specific spark-containment systems."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "key": "203-3a-teach-check-1",
      "title": "Principles of Circuit Types",
      "objective": "Describe the operational principles and applications of lighting, power, ring final, and radial circuits.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Every electrical installation is divided into specific circuits based on the load they serve and how they are wired. A Radial Circuit is the most straightforward type; it runs from the consumer unit to the points of use and ends at the final outlet, much like a single branch on a tree. While common for lighting, radials are also used for high-power appliances like cookers or showers.",
        "In contrast, a Ring Final Circuit forms a continuous loop. It starts at the consumer unit, passes through every socket-outlet, and returns to the same starting point. This design shares the electrical load between two paths, allowing the circuit to handle more equipment safely. Beyond standard power, you will encounter specialized circuits: data comms for networking, control circuits for operating machinery, and emergency circuits for fire alarms. Each type is chosen based on its specific job; for instance, an emergency circuit must be wired to remain functional even during a fire, whereas a data circuit is designed to prevent signal interference."
      ],
      "hint": "Focus on whether the circuit ends at the last point or returns to the source to form a loop."
    },
    {
      "key": "203-3a-teach-check-2",
      "title": "Wiring Systems and Environments",
      "objective": "Identify appropriate wiring systems such as SWA, MICC, and conduit for domestic, industrial, and hazardous environments.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "The environment of an installation dictates which wiring system is safe to use. In domestic settings, thermoplastic multicore cable is standard, but industrial or commercial sites require more robust protection. Conduit consists of rigid plastic or metal tubes used to shield individual cables from physical impact. If you need to manage large groups of cables along a wall, Trunking is used; unlike conduit, trunking features a rectangular profile with a removable lid for easy access.",
        "For high-risk areas, specialized cables are required. SWA (Steel Wire Armoured) cable features a layer of steel wires for heavy-duty mechanical protection, making it ideal for underground runs or factory floors. Note that the steel is for protection and earthing, not for carrying live current. In a Hazardous Environment where explosive gases or dust are present, wiring must be spark-proof. For fire-alarm systems or extremely high-heat areas, MICC (Mineral Insulated Copper Clad) is the essential choice. MICC is entirely fire-resistant because it uses mineral powder insulation and a copper sheath that will not burn or release toxic smoke."
      ],
      "hint": "Consider the level of physical danger, such as fire risk or mechanical impact, when selecting the system."
    }
  ]
}

